===Etymology===
French '''[[académie]]''' < {{L.}} '''[[academia|acadēmīa]]''' < {{AGr.}} '''{{polytonic|[[Ἀκαδήμια]]}}''' (Akadēmia), a grove of trees and gymnasium outside of Athens where [[w:Plato|Plato]] taught; from the name of the supposed former owner of that estate, the [[w:Attica|Attic]] hero [[w:Akademos|Akademos]]. Compare [[academe]], [[academia]], [[Akademeia]].

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/əˈkædəmi/}}, {{SAMPA|/@"k{d@mi/}}
*{{audio|en-us-academy.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|academ|ies}}

# A society of [[learned]] men united for the [[advancement]] of the arts and sciences, and literature, or some particular art or science; as, the [[French Academy]]; the American '''Academy''' of Arts and Sciences; '''academies''' of literature and [[philology]].
# A school or place of training in which some special art is taught; as, the military '''academy''' at West Point; a riding '''academy'''; the '''Academy''' of Music.
# An [[institution]] for the study of higher learning; a [[college]] or a [[university]].
# Popularly, a school, or [[seminary]] of learning, holding a rank between a college and a common school.
# A place of [[training]]; a school.
#:'''Quotations'''
